; A SAL program consists of comments, commands and symbolic
; expressions. Comments start with a semi-colon and appear in
; red. When SAL encounters a comment it ignores all the text until the
; end of that line.

; this is a comment

; A command is something that you execute to accomplish a task.
; Commands start in the very first column and appear in blue.  Here is
; a simple print command:

print "Hello, world!"

; To execute the command place your cursor at the end of the command
; line and press COMMAND-Enter. On the Mac the COMMAND key is the
; APPLE key just to the left of the space bar. On Windows and Linux
; the COMMAND key is the CONTROL key. Look in the Console window to
; see the results of executing the command.

; You can print lots if different things. Many or these expressions
; will involve math. In SAL math expressions, operators MUST be
; delimited by spaces. 

print 1 + 2 * 3 

; You can use parentheses to group and nest terms as you like. If you
; don't use parentheses then normal operator precedence applies:

print (1 + 2) * 3 

; Since we are using the print command a lot, notice that it can take
; more than one argument and that arguments are separated by
; commas. This next example prints a message an a new random key
; number every time you execute it:

print "my random key number: ", random(127)

; You will make lots mistakes as you learn. When you execute an
; expression that contains an error you will see an error message
; printed in the Console window. Sometimes this message is useful,
; sometimes its not so useful. Such is life.  Most mistakes involve
; parentheses or undefined terms, as demonstrated in these two
; examples:

print (1 + 2 * 3

print foo

; Because SAL is a language the commands and expressions you type can
; become quite complex and will often span more than one line.  Here
; is an example of a moderately complex command. To execute it, place
; your cursor just after the word 'end' and press COMMAND-Enter to see
; what it does.

begin
  with root = between(60, 90),
       third = root + pick(3,4) ,
       fifth = root + 7
   print "My random chord: ", note( list( root, third, fifth))
end

